{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501601"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:30:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:30:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1769"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1769"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.09,0.01,0.6,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1769"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83511"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1769"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1769"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68384"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"121"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"2115"},{"type":"tags","id":"8116"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5352"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7011"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28463"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83511"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 71-year-old man is being managed for an incidental finding made 12 months previously when he had a CT scan for an episode of diverticulitis. A 15 mm (diameter) mass was identified in the lower pole of the left kidney and a management decision was made for active surveillance with biannual imaging of the mass. His medical history includes stage II chronic kidney disease, hypertension, and hypercholesterolaemia. At his one-year surveillance CT, it is found that his mass has increased in size to 45 mm in diameter. There is no evidence of local invasion or metastatic disease.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate course of action at this stage?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continued active surveillance","Radiofrequency ablation","Chemotherapy","Partial nephrectomy","Radical nephrectomy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMost renal tumours are now picked up as incidental findings on imaging. Treatment will depend on tumour staging and the age and fitness of the patient. Active surveillance is appropriate for small tumours in patients with medical comorbidities that would increase the risk of surgery, including older age. However, as the mass has tripled in size over the past year, \u003Cstrong\u003Econtinued active surveillance\u003C/strong\u003E would be unwise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPartial nephrectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the preferred option for localised renal cell carcinoma, which is likely what this patient has. Furthermore, his established chronic kidney disease would make \u003Cstrong\u003Eradical nephrectomy\u003C/strong\u003E undesirable as it would put more strain on his remaining kidney. Partial nephrectomy is associated with better renal function and cardiovascular outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChemotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E has been shown to be ineffective in renal cell carcinoma and should not be given.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt present\u003Cstrong\u003E radiofrequency ablation\u003C/strong\u003E is considered experimental in the approach to management of renal cell carcinomas and is only used in the setting of clinical trials due to insufficient evidence to offer it as treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Localised renal tumours are better managed by partial nephrectomy than radical nephrectomy.","Partial nephrectomy preserves renal function and is preferred in patients with pre-existing chronic kidney disease.","Active surveillance is appropriate for small renal masses but should be reconsidered if there is significant growth."],"references":["Rao K, Royce PL. Incidentally detected small renal masses - investigation and management. Aust Fam Physician. 2011 Oct;40(10):776-82. PMID: 22003479. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22003479/","EAU [Internet]. Arnhem (The Netherlands): European Association of Urology; 2022. Renal Cell Carcinoma; [updated 2022; cited 2022 Sep 07]. Available from: https://uroweb.org/guidelines/renal-cell-carcinoma/","Long CJ, Canter DJ, Kutikov A, Li T, Simhan J, Smaldone M, Teper E, Viterbo R, Boorjian SA, Chen DY, Greenberg RE, Uzzo RG. Partial nephrectomy for renal masses \u2265 7 cm: technical, oncological and functional outcomes. BJU Int. 2012 May;109(10):1450-6. doi: 10.1111/j.1464-410X.2011.10608.x. Epub 2012 Jan 5. PMID: 22221502. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22221502/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68384"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1769"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68384","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68384"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-04T20:56:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-04T20:57:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1769"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83511"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09: